==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sceptre
<hw>Scep"tre</hw> }</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>sceptre</ets>, L. <ets>sceptrum</ets>, from
Gr. <?/ a staff to lean upon, a scepter; probably akin to E.
<ets>shaft</ets>. See <er>Shaft</er>, and cf. <er>Scape</er> a stem,
shaft.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A staff or baton borne by a sovereign, as
a ceremonial badge or emblem of authority; a royal mace.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And the king held out Esther the golden <qex>scepter</qex> that
was in his hand.</q> <rj><qau>Esther v. 2.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, royal or imperial power or authority;
sovereignty; <as>as, to assume the <ex>scepter</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>scepter</qex> shall not depart from Judah, nor a lawgiver
from between his feet, until Shiloh come.</q> <rj><qau>Gen. xlix.
10.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sceptre</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Scepter</ent>⟦br⟧
<mhw>{

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sceptre
<hw>Scep"tre</hw> }</mhw>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Sceptered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>
or <conjf>Sceptred</conjf> (<?/); <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Sceptering</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr> or <conjf>Sceptring</conjf>
<pr>(<?/)</pr>.]</vmorph> <def>To endow with the scepter, or emblem of
authority; to invest with royal authority.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To Britain's queen the <qex>sceptered</qex> suppliant bends.</q>
<rj><qau>Tickell.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scepterellate</ent>⟦br⟧
